<section xml:id="section-solving-systems-of-linear-equations-by-graphing">
  <title>Solving Systems of Linear Equations by Graphing</title>
  <objectives>
    <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-solve-system-of-linear-equations" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
      </li>

      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-model-with-systems" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      We have learned how to graph a line given its equation.
      In this section, we will learn what a <em>system</em>
      of <em>two</em> linear equations is,
      and how to use graphing to solve such a system.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
      <video youtubeplaylist="PLmuZCPhWPt-c8HMsuhb9oJTIJBEvrrZiH" />
    </figure>
  </introduction>

  <subsection>
    <title>Solving Systems of Equations by Graphing</title>
    <idx><h>solving</h><h>system of linear equations</h><h>graphing</h></idx>

    <example xml:id="example-solving-systems-by-graphing-intro">
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

        <stack>
          <p>
            Fabiana and David are running at constant speeds in parallel lanes on a track.
            David starts out ahead of Fabiana,
            but Fabiana is running faster.
            We want to determine when Fabiana will catch up with David.
            Let's start by looking at the graph of each runner's distance over time,
            in <xref ref="figure-solving-systems-by-graphing-intro">Figure</xref>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Each of the two lines has an equation,
            as discussed in <xref ref="chapter-graphing-lines">Chapter</xref>.
            The line representing David appears to have <m>y</m>-intercept <m>(0,4)</m> and slope <m>\frac{4}{3}</m>,
            so its equation is <m>y=\frac{4}{3}t+4</m>.
            The line representing Fabiana appears to have <m>y</m>-intercept <m>(0,0)</m> and slope <m>2</m>,
            so its equation is <m>y=2t</m>.
          </p>
        </stack>

        <figure xml:id="figure-solving-systems-by-graphing-intro">
          <caption>David and Fabiana's distances.</caption>
          <image>
            <description>a coordinate plane with a line for David and a line for Fabiana; the horizontal scale is 1 second and the vertical scale is 2 meters; David's line has a y-intercept of (0,4) and Fabiana's line has a y-intercept of (0,0); the lines cross at the point (6,12)</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xlabel={$t$, time (in seconds)},
                            ylabel={$y$, distance (in meters)},
                            xmin=-1,xmax=10,
                            ymin=-1,ymax=15,
                            xtick={1,2,...,9},
                            minor xtick={1,2,...,9},
                            ytick={2,4,...,14},
                            minor ytick={2,4,...,14},
                            ]
                    \addplot[firstcurve,domain = 0:8.25,->]{4/3*x+4} node[pos=0.15,sloped,above] {David};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=firstcolor] coordinates {(0,4)};
                    \addplot[secondcurve,domain = 0:7.5,->]{2*x} node[pos=0.2,sloped,above] {Fabiana};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(0,0)};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=thirdcolor] coordinates {(6, 12)} node[pos=0.25,below right] {$(6,12)$};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>
      </sidebyside>

      <p>
        When these two equations are together as a package,
        we have what is called a <q>system of linear equations</q>:
        <me>
          \left\{
          \begin{alignedat}{4}
          y \amp {}={} \tfrac{4}{3}t \amp {}+{} \amp 4 \\
          y \amp {}={} 2t
          \end{alignedat}
          \right.
        </me>
        The large left brace indicates that this is a collection of two distinct equations,
        not one equation that was somehow algebraically manipulated into an equivalent equation.
      </p>

      <p>
        As we can see in <xref ref="figure-solving-systems-by-graphing-intro">Figure</xref>,
        the graphs of the two equations cross at the point <m>(6,12)</m>.
        We refer to the point <m>(6,12)</m> as the
        solution to this system of linear equations.
        To denote the solution set,
        we write <m>\{(6,12)\}</m>.
        It's more valuable to interpret these numbers in context whenever possible:
        it took <m>6</m> seconds for the two runners to meet up,
        and when they met they were <m>12</m> meters up the track.
      </p>
    </example>

    <definition xml:id="definition-system-of-linear-equations">
      <title>System of Linear Equations</title>
      <idx><h>system of linear equations</h></idx>
      <idx><h>solution</h><h>to a system of linear equations</h></idx>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>system of linear equations</term> is any pairing of two (or more) linear equations.
          A <term>solution to a system of linear equations</term>
          is any point that is a solution for all of the equations in the system.
          The <term>solution set to a system of linear equations</term> is the collection of all solutions to the system.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <remark>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="example-solving-systems-by-graphing-intro">Example</xref>,
        we stated that the solution was the point <m>(6,12)</m>.
        It makes sense to write this as an ordered pair when we're given a graph.
        In some cases when we have no graph,
        particularly when our variables are not <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
        it might not be clear which variable <q>comes first</q>
        and we won't be able to write an ordered pair.
        Nevertheless,
        given the context we can write meaningful summary statements.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine the solution to the system of equations graphed in <xref ref="figure-solve-using-graph">Figure</xref>.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="figure-solve-using-graph">
          <caption>Graph of a System of Equations</caption>
          <image width="47%">
            <description>A Cartesian plot with two intersecting lines; One line has a y-intercept of -2 and a slope of -1/4; the other line has a y-intercept of 5 and a slope of 2</description>

            <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[]
                        \addplot[firstcurve]expression[domain=-7:7]{-1/3*x-2};
                        \addplot[secondcurve]expression[domain=-6:1]{2*x+5};
                    \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The two lines intersect where <m>x=-3</m> and <m>y=-1</m>,
          so the solution is the point <m>(-3,-1)</m>.
          We write the solution set as <m>\{(-3,-1)\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <webwork>
            <pg-code>
                $gr = init_graph(-7,-7,7,7,
                    axes=>[0,0],
                    grid=>[14,14],
                    size=>[240,240]);
                $gr->lb('reset');
                for $j (-6..6) {
                   $gr->lb( new Label($j,0,$j,'black','center','top','large'));
                }
                for $j (-6..6) {
                   if (Real($j) == 0) {next;}
                   $gr->lb( new Label(0,$j,$j,'black','right','middle','large'));
                }
                $gr->moveTo(3,2);
                $gr->arrowTo(7,6,'blue',1);
                $gr->moveTo(3,2);
                $gr->arrowTo(-6,-7,'blue',1);
                $gr->moveTo(3,2);
                $gr->arrowTo(7,-2,'red',1);
                $gr->moveTo(3,2);
                $gr->arrowTo(-2,7,'red',1);
                Context("Point");
            </pg-code>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Determine the solution to the system of equations graphed below.
            </p>

            <image pg-name="$gr" width="40%"/>

            <p>
              The solution is the point <var name="'(3,2)'" width="20" />.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              The two lines intersect where <m>x=3</m> and <m>y=2</m>,
              so the solution is the point <m>(3,2)</m>.
              We write the solution set as <m>\{(3,2)\}</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      Now let's look at an example where <em>we</em>
      need to make a graph to find the solution.
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Solve the following system of equations by graphing:
        <me>
          \left\{
          \begin{alignedat}{4}
          y \amp {}={} \amp \tfrac{1}{2}x \amp {}+{} \amp 4 \\
          y \amp {}={} \amp {-x} \amp {}-{} \amp 5
          \end{alignedat}
          \right.
        </me>
      </p>

      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

        <stack>
          <p>
            Notice that each of these equations is written in slope-intercept form.
            The first equation, <m>y=\frac{1}{2}x+4</m>,
            is a linear equation with a slope of
            <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> and a <m>y</m>-intercept of <m>(0,4)</m>.
            The second equation, <m>y=-x-5</m>,
            is a linear equation with a slope of <m>-1</m> and a <m>y</m>-intercept of <m>(0,-5)</m>.
            We'll use this information to graph both lines.
          </p>

          <p>
            It appears that the two lines intersect where <m>x=-6</m> and <m>y=1</m>,
            so the solution of the system of equations would be the point <m>(-6,1)</m>.
            We should check this with the two original equations.
            <md>
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}x+4\amp y\amp=-x-5</mrow>
              <mrow>\substitute{1}\amp\wonder{=}\frac{1}{2}(\substitute{-6})+4\amp \substitute{1}\amp\wonder{=}-(\substitute{-6})-5</mrow>
              <mrow>1\amp\confirm{=}-3+4\amp 1\amp\confirm{=}6-5</mrow>
            </md>
            This verifies that <m>(-6,1)</m> is the solution,
            and we write the solution set as <m>\{(-6,1)\}</m>.
          </p>
        </stack>

        <figure>
          <caption><m>y=\frac{1}{2}x+4</m> and <m>y=-x-5</m>.</caption>
          <image>
            <description>A Cartesian grid with two intersecting lines; one line has a y-intercept of 4 and a slope of 1/2; the other line has a y-intercept of -5 and a slope of -1</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[]
                    \addplot[firstcurve]expression[domain=-7:6]{1/2*x+4} node[pos=0.25,sloped,above] {$y=\frac{1}{2}x+4$};
                    \addplot[secondcurve]expression[domain=-7:2]{-1*x-5} node[pos=0.5,sloped,below] {$y=-x-5$};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,4) (2,4) (2,5)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,4) (-2,4) (-2,3)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,-5) (1,-5) (1,-6)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,-5) (-1,-5) (-1,-4)};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=firstcolor] coordinates {(0,4) (2,5) (-2,3) };
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(0,-5) (1,-6) (-1,-4)};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the following system of equations by graphing:
          <me>
            \left\{
            \begin{alignedat}{3}
            x \amp {}-{} \amp 3y \amp {}={} \amp {-12} \\
            2x \amp {}+{} \amp 3y \amp {}={} \amp 3
            \end{alignedat}
            \right.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Since both line equations are given in standard form,
          we'll graph each one by finding the intercepts.
          Recall that to find the <m>x</m>-intercept of each equation,
          replace <m>y</m> with <m>0</m> and solve for <m>x</m>.
          Similarly, to find the <m>y</m>-intercept of each equation,
          replace <m>x</m> with <m>0</m> and solve for <m>y</m>.
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            For our first linear equation, we have:
            <md>
              <mrow>x-3(\substitute{0}) \amp= -12 \amp \substitute{0}-3y \amp=-12</mrow>
              <mrow>x \amp= -12 \amp -3y \amp= -12</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp\amp y\amp= 4</mrow>
            </md>.
            So the intercepts are <m>(-12,0)</m> and <m>(0,4)</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            For our second linear equation, we have:
            <md>
              <mrow>2x+3(\substitute{0}) \amp= 3\amp 2(\substitute{0})+3y \amp= 3</mrow>
              <mrow>2x \amp= 3\amp 3y \amp= 3</mrow>
              <mrow>x \amp= \frac{3}{2}\amp y\amp= 1</mrow>
            </md>.
            So the intercepts are <m>\left(\frac{3}{2},0\right)</m> and <m>(0,1)</m>.
          </p>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>
          Now we can graph each line by plotting the intercepts and connecting these points:
        </p>

        <figure>
          <caption>Graphs of <m>x-3y=-12</m> and <m>2x+3y=3</m></caption>
          <image width="47%">
            <description>a Cartesian plot with two intersecting lines; one line has a y-intercept of 4 and an x-intercept of -12; the other line has a y-intercept of 1 and an x-intercept of 3/2</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                            xmin=-15,xmax=15,
                            ymin=-7,ymax=7,
                            xtick={-10,-5,...,10},
                            minor xtick={-15,-14,...,15},
                            ytick={-6,-4,...,6},
                            minor ytick={-7,-6,...,7},
                            ]
                        \addplot[firstcurve,domain=-15:9]{1/3*x+4} node[pos=0.8,sloped,below] {$x-3y=-12$};
                        \addplot[soliddot,color=firstcolor] coordinates {(-12,0) (0,4)};
                        \addplot[secondcurve,domain=-9:12]{-2/3*x+1} node[pos=0.8,sloped,below] {$2x+3y=3$};
                        \addplot[soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(1.5,0) (0,1)};
                        \addplot[soliddot,color=thirdcolor] coordinates {(-3,3)} node[left] {$(-3,3)$};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>

        <p>
          It appears that the solution of the system of equations is the point of intersection of those two lines,
          which is <m>(-3,3)</m>.
          It's important to check this is correct,
          because when making a hand-drawn graph,
          it would be easy to be off by a little bit.
          To check, we can substitute the values of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> from the point <m>(-3,3)</m> into each equation:
          <md>
            <mrow>x-3y \amp=-12\amp 2x+3y \amp= 3</mrow>
            <mrow>\substitute{-3}-3(\substitute{3}) \amp\wonder{=}-12 \amp 2(\substitute{-3})+3(\substitute{3}) \amp\wonder{=} 3</mrow>
            <mrow>-3-9 \amp\confirm{=}-12 \amp -6+9 \amp\confirm{=} 3</mrow>
          </md>
          So we have checked that <m>(-3,3)</m> is indeed the solution for the system.
          We write the solution set as <m>\{(-3,3)\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A college has a north campus and a south campus.
          The north campus has <m>18{,}000</m> students,
          and the south campus has <m>4{,}000</m> students.
          In the past five years, the north campus lost <m>4{,}000</m> students,
          and the south campus gained <m>3{,}000</m> students.
          If these trends continue,
          in how many years would the two campuses have the same number of students?
          Write and solve a system of equations modeling this problem.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Since all the given student counts are in the thousands,
          we make the decision to measure student population in thousands.
          So for instance,
          the north campus starts with a student population of <m>18</m>
          (thousand students).
        </p>

        <p>
          The north campus lost <m>4</m> thousand students in <m>5</m> years.
          So it is losing students at a rate of <m>\frac{4\text{ thousand}}{5\text{ year}}</m>,
          or <m>\frac{4}{5}\,\frac{\text{thousand}}{\text{year}}</m>.
          This rate of change should be interpreted as a negative number,
          because the north campus is losing students over time.
          So we have a linear model with starting value <m>18</m> thousand students,
          and a slope of <m>-\frac{4}{5}</m> thousand students per year.
          In other words,
          <me>
            y=-\frac{4}{5}t+18
          </me>,
          where <m>y</m> stands for the number of students in thousands,
          and <m>t</m> stands for the number of years into the future.
        </p>

        <p>
          Similarly, the number of students at the south campus can be modeled by <m>y=\frac{3}{5}t+4</m>.
          Now we have a system of equations:
          <md>
            <mrow>\left\{
            \begin{alignedat}{4}
            y \amp {}={} \amp {-\frac{4}{5}}t \amp {}+{} \amp 18 \\
            y \amp {}={} \amp \frac{3}{5}t \amp {}+{} \amp 4
            \end{alignedat}
            \right.</mrow>
          </md>
          We will graph both lines using their slopes and <m>y</m>-intercepts.
        </p>

        <figure>
          <caption>Number of Students at the South Campus and North Campus</caption>
          <image width="50%">
            <description>a coordinate plot with two intersecting lines; the North campus line has a y-intercept of 18 and a slope of -4/5; the South campus line has a y-intercept of 4 and a slope of 3/5</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xlabel={$t$, years},
                            ylabel={$y$, number of students (in thousands)},
                            xmin=-1,xmax=12,
                            ymin=-1,ymax=21,
                            xtick={1,2,...,11},
                            minor xtick={1,2,...,11},
                            ytick={2,4,...,20},
                            minor ytick={2,4,...,20},
                            ]
                    \addplot[firstcurve,domain = 0:12,->]{-4/5*x+18} node[pos=0.25,sloped,above] {North};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=firstcolor] coordinates {(0,18)};
                    \addplot[secondcurve,domain = 0:12,->]{3/5*x+4} node[pos=0.25,sloped,above] {South};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(0,4)};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=thirdcolor] coordinates {(10, 10)} node[above] {$(10,10)$};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>

        <p>
          According to the graph, the lines intersect at <m>(10,10)</m>.
          So if the trends continue,
          both campuses will have <m>10{,}000</m> students <m>10</m> years from now.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the following system of equations by graphing:
          <me>
            \left\{
            \begin{alignedat}{3}
            y \amp {}={} \amp 3(x-2) \amp {}+{} \amp 1 \\
            y \amp {}={} \amp -\tfrac{1}{2}(x+1) \amp {}-{} \amp 1
            \end{alignedat}
            \right.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Since both line equations are given in <xref ref="definition-point-slope-form" text="custom">point-slope form</xref>,
          we can start by graphing the point indicated in each equation and use the slope to determine the rest of the line.
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            For our first equation, <m>y=3(x-2)+1</m>,
            the point indicated in the equation is <m>(2,1)</m> and the slope is <m>3</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            For our second equation, <m>y=-\frac{1}{2}(x+1)-1</m>,
            the point indicated in the equation is <m>(-1,-1)</m> and the slope is <m>-\frac{1}{2}</m>.
          </p>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>
          Now we can graph each line by plotting the points and using their slopes.
        </p>

        <figure>
          <caption>Graphs of <m>y=3(x-2)+1</m> and <m>y=-\frac{1}{2}(x+1)-1</m></caption>
          <image width="47%">
            <description>a Cartesian plot with two intersecting lines; one line passes through the point (2,1) with a slope of 3; the other line passes through the point (-1,-1) with a slope of -1/2.</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                            xmin=-7,xmax=7,
                            ymin=-7,ymax=7,
                            xtick={-6,-4,...,6},
                            minor xtick={-7,-6,...,7},
                            ytick={-6,-4,...,6},
                            minor ytick={-7,-6,...,7},
                            ]
                        \addplot[firstcurve,domain=-0.6666:4]{3*(x-2)+1} node[pos=0.67,sloped,above] {$y=3(x-2)+1$};
                        \addplot[soliddot,color=firstcolor] coordinates {(2,1)};
                        \addplot[secondcurve,domain=-7:7]{-1/2*(x+1)-1} node[pos=0.23,sloped,above] {$y=-\frac{1}{2}(x+1)-1$};
                        \addplot[soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(-1,-1)};
                        \addplot[soliddot,color=thirdcolor] coordinates {(1,-2)} node[right] {$(1,-2)$};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>

        <p>
          It appears that the solution of the system of equations is the point of intersection of those two lines,
          which is <m>(1,-2)</m>.
          It's important to check this is correct,
          because when making a hand-drawn graph,
          it would be easy to be off by a little bit.
          To check, we can substitute the values of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> from the point <m>(1,-2)</m> into each equation:
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>y\amp=3(x-2)+1</mrow>
              <mrow>\substitute{-2}\amp\wonder{=}3(\substitute{1}-2)+1</mrow>
              <mrow>-2\amp\wonder{=}3(-1)+1</mrow>
              <mrow>-2\amp\confirm{=}-3+1</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{1}{2}(x+1)-1</mrow>
              <mrow>\substitute{-2}\amp\wonder{=}-\frac{1}{2}(\substitute{1}+1)-1</mrow>
              <mrow>-2\amp\wonder{=}-\frac{1}{2}(2)-1</mrow>
              <mrow>-2\amp\confirm{=}-1-1</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>
          So we have checked that <m>(2,-1)</m> is indeed the solution for the system.
          We write the solution set as <m>\{(2,-1)\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsection-special-systems-of-equations">
    <title>Special Systems of Equations</title>
    <p>
      Recall that when we solved linear equations in one variable,
      there were two special cases discussed in detail in <xref ref="section-special-solution-sets">Section</xref>.
      In one special case, like with the equation <m>x=x+1</m>, there is no solution.
      And in the another case, like with the equation <m>x=x</m>,
      there are infinitely many solutions.
      When solving systems of equations in two variables,
      we have similar special cases to consider.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="example-solving-systems-by-graphing-parallel-lines">
      <title>Parallel Lines</title>
      <p>
        Let's look at the graphs of two lines with the same slope,
        <m>y=2x-4</m> and <m>y=2x+1</m>:
      </p>

      <figure>
        <caption>Graphs of <m>y=2x-4</m> and <m>y=2x+1</m></caption>
        <image width="50%">
          <description>a coordinate grid with two parallel lines; one line has a y-intercept of -4 and the other has a y-intercept of 1; they both have a slope of 2</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[]
                    \addplot[firstcurve,domain = -1.5:5.5]{2*x-4} node[pos=0.75,sloped,below] {$y=2x-4$};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=firstcolor] coordinates {(0,-4) (1,-2) (2,0)};
                    \addplot[secondcurve,domain = -4:3]{2*x+1} node[pos=0.75,sloped,below] {$y=2x+1$};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(0,1) (1,3) (2,5)};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
        </image>

      </figure>

      <p>
        For this system of equations, what is the solution?
        Since the two lines have the same slope they are
        <term>parallel lines</term>
        and will never intersect.
        This means that there is <em>no solution</em>
        to this system of equations.
        We write the solution set as <m>\emptyset</m>.
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      The symbol <m>\emptyset</m> is a special symbol that represents the <term>empty set</term>,
      a <em>set</em> that has no numbers in it which can also be written simply as <m>\{\text{ }\}</m>.
        <idx><h>empty set</h></idx>
      This symbol is <em>not</em> the same thing as the number zero.
      The <em>number</em> of eggs in an empty egg carton is zero whereas the empty carton itself could represent the empty set.
      The symbols for the empty set and the number zero may look similar depending on how you write the number zero,
      so try to keep the concepts separate.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="example-solving-systems-by-graphing-equivalent-equations">
      <title>Coinciding Lines</title>
      <p>
        Next we'll look at the other special case.
        Let's start with this system of equations:
        <me>
          \left\{
          \begin{alignedat}{4}
          y \amp {}={} \amp 2x-4 \\
          6x-3y \amp {}={} \amp 12
          \end{alignedat}
          \right.
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        To solve this system of equations,
        we want to graph each line.
        The first equation is in slope-intercept form and can be graphed easily using its slope of <m>2</m> and its <m>y</m>-intercept of <m>(0,-4)</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        The second equation, <m>6x-3y=12</m>,
        can either be graphed by solving for <m>y</m> and using the slope-intercept form or by finding the intercepts.
        If we use the intercept method,
        we'll find that this line has an <m>x</m>-intercept of <m>(2,0)</m> and a <m>y</m>-intercept of <m>(0,-4)</m>.
        When we graph both lines we get <xref ref="figure-coinciding-lines">Figure</xref>.
      </p>

      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <p>
          Now we can see these are actually the <em>same</em> line,
          or <term>coinciding lines</term>.
          To determine the solution to this system,
          we'll note that they overlap everywhere.
          This means that we have an infinite number of solutions:
          <em>all</em> points that fall on the line.
          It may be enough to report that there are infinitely many solutions.
          In order to be more specific,
          all we can do is say that any ordered pair <m>(x,y)</m> satisfying the line equation is a solution.
          In set-builder notation, we would write <m>\{(x,y)\mid y=2x-4\}</m>.
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="figure-coinciding-lines">
          <caption>Graphs of <m>y=2x-4</m> and <m>6x-3y=12</m></caption>
          <image width="50%">
            <description>a coordinate plot of two lines that are coinciding; they both have a y-intercept of (0,-4) and a slope of 2</description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[]
                    \addplot[firstcurve,domain = -1.5:5.5]{2*x-4.1} node[pos=0.75,sloped,below] {$y=2x-4$};
                    \addplot[secondcurve,domain = -1.5:5.5]{2*x-4} node[pos=0.75,sloped,above] {$6x-3y=12$};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=firstcolor] coordinates {(0,-4.1) (1,-2.1) (2,-0.1)};
                    \addplot[soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(0,-4) (2,0)};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>

        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="example-solving-systems-by-graphing-equivalent-equations">Example</xref>,
        what would have happened if we had decided to convert the second line equation into slope-intercept form?
        <md>
          <mrow>6x-3y\amp=12</mrow>
          <mrow>6x-3y\subtractright{6x}\amp=12\subtractright{6x}</mrow>
          <mrow>-3y\amp=-6x+12</mrow>
          <mrow>\multiplyleft{-\frac{1}{3}}(-3y)\amp=\multiplyleft{-\frac{1}{3}}(-6x+12)</mrow>
          <mrow>y\amp=2x-4</mrow>
        </md>
        This is the literally the same as the first equation in our system.
        This is a different way to show that these two equations are equivalent and represent the same line.
        Any time we try to solve a system where the equations are equivalent,
        we'll have an infinite number of solutions.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <warning>
      <p>
        Notice that for a system of equations with infinite solutions like <xref ref="example-solving-systems-by-graphing-equivalent-equations">Example</xref>,
        we didn't say that <em>every</em> point was a solution.
        Rather, <em>every point that falls on that line</em> is a solution.
        It would be incorrect to state this solution set as
        <q>all real numbers</q>
        or as <q>all ordered pairs.</q>
      </p>
    </warning>

    <list xml:id="list-summary-of-types-of-systems">
      <title>A summary of the three types of systems of equations and their solution sets.</title>
      <dl>
        <li>
          <title>Intersecting Lines:</title>
          <p>
            If two linear equations make lines with different slopes,
            the system has one solution.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Parallel Lines:</title>
          <p>
            If two linear equations make lines with the same slope but different <m>y</m>-intercepts,
            the system has no solution.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Coinciding Lines:</title>
          <p>
            If two linear equations make lines with the same slope and the same <m>y</m>-intercept
            (in other words, they make the same line),
            the system has infinitely many solutions.
            This solution set consists of all ordered pairs on that line.
          </p>
        </li>
      </dl>
    </list>
  </subsection>

